			<div id="tableofcontents">
			<h2>February &ndash; March 2009<br /><span class="volumeinfo">Vol VIII No 2</span></h2>
			<h3>IT Policy And The Road To Open Government</h3>
			<!-- INDEX ITEM -->
			<p><span class="section">EDITOR'S NOTE:</span><br /><span class="title"><a href="#editorsnote" title="Editors Note" accesskey="1">With Access and Information for All</a></span></p>
			<p>Over the last two hundred years, poll taxes, literacy tests and other artificial barriers have too often stood between the less privileged and the exercise of their rights of citizenship. Will the migration of government services to the Web be a great leap forward, or an avoidably negligent step back?<br /><a class="pdf" href="/bulletins/pdf/feb09/feb09_editorsnote.pdf">Download PDF</a></p>
			
			<!-- INDEX ITEM -->
			<p><span class="section">EDITORIAL:</span><br /><span class="title"><a href="#editorial" title="Editorial" accesskey="2">Enabling Open Government</a></span></p>
			<p>The Obama Administration has committed to creating an "unprecedented level of openness in government," made possible by an equally ambitious utilization of information technology.  How that technology, and the standards upon which it relies, are selected will determine whether open government is made available to all, or only to  the technically sophisticated, the able-bodied, and the well to do.<br /><a class="pdf" href="/bulletins/pdf/feb09/feb09_editorial.pdf">Download PDF</a></p>
			
			<!-- INDEX ITEM -->
			<p><span class="section">FEATURE ARTICLE:</span><br /><span class="title"><a href="#feature" title="Feature Article" accesskey="3">How Open Must Open Government Platforms be?</a></span></p>
			<p>Governments represent some of the most complex enterprises in existence, typically comprising multiple "silos" of high-value information trapped within proprietary legacy systems. Government CIOs today are struggling to upgrade their vast IT systems to exchange information across the enterprise, even as President Obama has called upon them to make much of the same information publicly accessible via the Internet.  What should the result look like, and why?<br /><a class="pdf" href="/bulletins/pdf/feb09/feb09_feature.pdf">Download PDF</a></p>
			
			<!-- INDEX ITEM -->
			<p><span class="section">STANDARDS BLOG:</span><br /><span class="title"><a href="#blog" title="Standards Blog" accesskey="4">"Openness," the Customer and the IDABC</a></span></p>
			<p>"Openness" in technology means different things to different people in different settings, because different settings attract different participants with different goals.  What should it mean to governments?<br /><a class="pdf" href="/bulletins/pdf/feb09/feb09_blog.pdf">Download PDF</a></p>
			
			<!-- INDEX ITEM -->
			<p><span class="section">CONSIDER THIS:</span><br /><span class="title"><a href="#considerthis" title="Consider This" accesskey="5">Killing the Cockroach:  The Incredibly Illogical, Fundamentally Odious &mdash; but Seemingly Ineradicable &mdash; Billable Hour</a></span></p>
			<p>You'd never write a blank check to a house painter to paint your house.  So why hand one to a lawyer?  Good question.<br /><a class="pdf" href="/bulletins/pdf/feb09/feb09_considerthis.pdf">Download PDF</a></p>
			
